# Rule 030 - Buy vs. Build

A solo founder's time is the tightest resource. For commodity capabilities, a paid tool beats a custom build every single time until scale forces a rebuild.

## The buy list (defaults)

Before generating code for any of the capability classes below, open an ADR titled `buy-vs-build-<capability>.md` under `.planning/adr/` and justify the build path explicitly. Without that ADR, use the default service.

| Capability | Default service(s) | When custom is defensible |
|---|---|---|
| CRM | Airtable, Notion, HubSpot Free | Contact volume > 10k AND custom relationship model |
| Analytics | Plausible, Umami, PostHog Cloud | EU privacy-sensitive AND sub-200ms self-host latency need |
| Auth | Clerk, Supabase Auth, Auth.js | SSO complexity beyond vendor offering |
| Payments | Stripe, Paddle, Lemon Squeezy | Non-standard settlement (marketplace split, crypto) |
| Email | Resend, Loops, Postmark | Millions of sends / month |
| File storage | Supabase Storage, Cloudflare R2, S3 | Special compliance (HIPAA zero-trust, etc.) |
| Search | Algolia, Meilisearch Cloud, Typesense Cloud | Custom ranking with proprietary data signals |
| Forms | Typeform, Tally | Complex conditional logic tied to internal state |
| Scheduling | Cal.com, SavvyCal | Custom availability engine tied to product |

## Enforcement

- If an agent suggests building one of the above from scratch, ask the user whether an ADR exists.
- If no ADR exists, refuse the build and propose the relevant default instead.
- If the user says "I want to build it myself for learning", accept only when `.planning/COMMERCIAL/METRICS.md` shows < 3 paying customers AND the user confirms the learning-over-revenue tradeoff. Log the decision as an ADR either way.

## Rationale

Troy 1.2 + 1.6: speed to 10 paying customers matters more than code ownership. Every hour spent rebuilding commodity infra is an hour not spent on the commercial track.
